  {
    "@type": "Event",
    "name": "Private Preview of -  A Moving Line: 1500 years of Indian Visual Storytelling",
    "url": "https://puttingscene.com/events/5253",
    "startDate": "2026-07-24T18:00:00+05:30",
    "endDate": "2026-07-24T20:00:00+05:30",
    "description": "<p><strong>About the experience</strong></p><p>Carved into Bengaluru's Someshwara temple in Halasuru is one of the city's earliest examples of sequential storytelling \u2014 a line cut in stone. <em>A Moving Line</em>, curated by graphic novelist <strong>Amruta Patil</strong>, traces that same impulse across 1,500 years and 250+ works, from <em>kaavad</em> and <em>pattachitra</em> scrolls to <em>Amar Chitra Katha</em>, <em>Tinkle</em>, <em>Chacha Chaudhary</em>, and the <em>Phantom</em>, through to today's graphic novels and webcomics.</p><p>Rooted in MAP's commitment to accessibility, the exhibition includes tactile and audio elements, Indian Sign Language content, an audio guide, described content, and books to browse, with a facilitator on hand for walkthroughs and a hands-on activity inviting visitors to build their own comic.</p><p>The show is accompanied by a publication featuring an introduction by Amruta Patil and newly commissioned essays and graphic narratives.</p><p><em>Follow a single line from a temple wall to a touchscreen \u2014 and watch a country tell its stories.</em></p>",
    "image": "https://cdn.puttingscene.com/event_images/5253/4212cab5-3d73-40c6-8ccc-422b384b5057.jpg",
    "location": {
      "name": "Museum of Art & Photography (MAP)",
      "address": "Museum of Art & Photography (MAP), ",
      "url": "https://maps.google.com/?cid=9228804832244306612"
    },
    "isAccessibleForFree": true
  },
